This psychological meaning of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is most important at the moment," said Marek.
An extreme fight: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems to be clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
There are sufficient reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a cheap high-end grammophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
But if there are vinyl records in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you’re probably dreaming of such a grammophone.
The same is the same for music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to say simplifiedly - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way as a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble to support the headphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
Here are two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, telephone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and films, record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, be used to navigate.
And if you take into account smartphones and communications, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Because no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television takes photographs, we almost watch a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the more the interval between two recharges will be reduced.
And playing music is one of the most important energy flows.
There are rare mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this number is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (specially the most rudimentary) are significantly more effective.
In the case of cheap mobiles, consider that they will only play music for a few hours.
In addition, if you sometimes call from time to time, get a second recharge for work - this is valid even for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are able to, as a result of a recharge, continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially because not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Obviously, you can record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know to take it without reduction, being given the small dimensions of the memory cards used in the mobiles.
With regard to the readers, you do not need any software, except for the exception (iPod).
Just fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library ranked by the interpreter’s name, the title of the album, style, or the user’s judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a shaft structure, as Windows Explore, others are capable of both (irriting, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, be particularly interested in the life of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and type of output of the sound and, of course, the ease of control.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and in the day you will hear that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you’ll just have any mobile reading the MP3s.
Almost all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone can play the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will just have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or other provider) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason to purchase a musical mobile.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to quickly made radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their mobile on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in boxes, which possess virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand crowns, you can have a very suitable walkman already.
In most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and best tools, also provided with an entry for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone can control the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily match the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a grammophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by an immense data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive are out of it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
