A first virtual operator will win Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in Czech is relatively advanced, our operators offer virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still miss something - a virtual operator, which would force classical operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Agency (Czech Telecommunications Agency), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed.
This is how, following the last steps of the European Commission in roaming fees regulation, a paradoxal situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really wish to enter the fight.
This may seem paradox, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that greatly exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this case, Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Board (Czech Telecommunications Board), who repeatedly stated that there was no room for another operator in Czech Republic, chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network apparently has no more luck (moreover, he would now find only frequencies hardly).
There is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators to the mobile market that resulted in a significant decrease in prices, which then also had to respond to conventional operators.
However, even before the entry of events such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today were left to hear in Britain.
But it appeared that there was a place for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We don’t have to go too far to find examples.
In February, we informed you of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only six months, this operator managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which, among other things, has the U:phone in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to make their operation effective, they indeed need much less customers than a conventional operator.
Indeed, they are exempt from the construction, operating and maintenance costs of the mobile network, relatively high.
This is how virtual operators in the world are profiling themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers at least twice cheaper SMS in Britain than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertising shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“The real men choose Mobilking – an operator who likes them and whom they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to walk at home as well.
Vodafone’s spokesman Miroslav Čepický, in doubt: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially because it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offering of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost sure that if there is a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czech, negotiations are not very promoting.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area,” said Jana Studničková, spokesman of the Penta Financial Group, in a phone host for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czech Republic were, in any case, not favourable to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator for long enough.
“We want a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the earlier it will be the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl Group spokesman.
The future may be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At this moment, we do not estimate there is place in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us,” said Vlastimil Sršeň, the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the statement of O2: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she added, "It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate within such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone rather directs his attention to the fulfillment of requests to obtain his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe mean most contributions from the customers' perspective.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
What is then good to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to understand themselves like thefts in fair. The chicane accompanied by the creation of the U:phone also testify to it.
The most apparent pressure on the ČTU, when the U:fon was created, was the pressure exercised by the T-Mobile company.
This provides evidence of information accessible to the public from the Internet pages of the CTU.
Now, the U:phone is promised to serve as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: “Competition in the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would submit it, and above all its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulatory agencies seems confusing.
However, it is not only about the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has not the power to intervene in economic competition in Czech Republic.
This belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
Now, the latter adopted, in the face of this issue, its typical position.
“The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile market would be possible as a result of the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders a priori has not presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," Kristián Chalupa, the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations, said in response to our question.
A statement made therefore would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But from an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care, so that no one benefits from its position in the market, such a statement is more than disturbing.
Especially as Kristián Chalupa adds: “Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be found that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices for mobile phone services.”
However, pressure in the direction of an honest market functioning and a decrease in prices apparently does not be part of the OHSU's interests.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which comes from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a chance, is naturally asked.
Similarly, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the random and hard competition fight.
"The office has not noted signs of an anti-competitive behaviour in this matter, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour in the market.
The tools needed for the opening of the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to lack even the telecom regulator,” said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of discord.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the ČTU, according to which telecommunications, from the point of view of economic competition, constitute a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some law experts propose another vision of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, you must obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least concerning for the UOHS that three mobile operators are visiblely performing in a similar manner.
However, complaints of many interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Retaining responsibility for the CTU is a fairly common tour in communications, through which the UOHS wash the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the newly adopted Telecommunications Act has not been introduced to an expansion of the powers of ČTU on the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised improvement in the situation.
This must be known very well by the UOHS representatives, but their interests are apparently different.
When no one looks, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price list of mobile phone services, but they are public only partly.
In most cases, it’s about multi-level marketing firms.
Specialized mobile phone services are thus offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected people.
The tour of magic consists of the fact that the company makes in front of the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the trade conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbid such a resell.
"If what you talk about happened, it might be a breach of the contractual conditions we would examine and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the society in question," Martina Kemrová said.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the responsible of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
Any operator, however, does not decide against such a proceedings.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them unforgettable profits, and at the same time, in contrast to the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, these are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not recorded under their name, so they cannot fully arrange it, as the ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But this is precisely what should seem strange in the CTU.
Furthermore, another question is asked at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why block the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the UOHS has relatively wide powers to be able to disclose such a activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned repeatedly, the entry of virtual operators to the mobile market has resulted in a significant decrease in service prices.
Now, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, classical operators were sometimes more, sometimes less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But precisely at that level, in developed countries, the regulatory agencies have been involved, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measurements and by informal pressure, they finally obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue in the manner of a hot potato that we get rid of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
Because of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in the skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the sleeve after the crack.
If the scenario information says true and a virtual operator will soon appear at us, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to create a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will hardly remain impassible in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national hymn.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new records of the national hymn Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was once again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the hymn.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care of that both singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that one can understand the words that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national hymn will celebrate its 175th birthday next year.
The song Kde domov můj sounded for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka, Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriate it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first coupling became naturally an integral part of the national hymn.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the Independent Czech Republic.
