Pragous public transport (MHD) will introduce chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragosian Transport Agency) will be entered as the date when the first passengers will climb to the subway, trams and bus, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and record it on their chip map at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located in the stations Muzeum, Můkastek, Ludrý and Rošovice
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy the internet coupons on the Dopravní podnik websites: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people benefited from the service during the morning.
Those who will begin to use the online store can forget definitively the tickets in the subway stations, where they so far had to catch up with long tails in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon on the internet and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the 13 Městská knihovna (Municipal Libraries).
“In these points of contact, there is available to the passengers a checkout with trained staff, which will help those interested in purchasing via the internet and, moreover, will record the coupon they bought on their map,” says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons will also be recorded on the Opencard in automatic distributors installed in the vestibule of several subway stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the ticket composting machines and the passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five of them, but by the end of the year, there should be ninety of them," Opatrný added.
An automat will control the coupon instead of the driver
The machines that are going to work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Just enter the Opencard chip card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surroundings of the city.
In other words, in periurban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of Central Bohemian municipalities mainly use to access the capital.
"In trains integrated in Pražská integrovaná doprava, controllers are equipped with card readers, with the aid of which they establish the temporary and zone validity of the coupons," explained the control of Filip Drápal tickets from the Ropid organization, which designs the timetables of the common transportation.
The periurban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver’s box.
When embarking it is therefore necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the place indicated on the side of the box.
This is how the driver controls the validity of the registered coupons.
