"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who do not care about moving on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stage performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the schedule of the Month of Flamenco Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, larger every day," explains the creator, which clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to convey on stage of passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture the moments of personality of these artists, you don’t have to take photos on the stage.
They have a personality and a clean character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars.”
With the "Popular Mines Chant" festival, Bauer began a long trip in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and equipment, remember the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylish means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of the flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day."
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the public with his art.
The search for the essential and magic has been the constant of this work presented these days at the El Fotómata Gallery.
Flamenco seedles such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exposed to the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, know them and be able to enter their lives for a moment more or less long.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You are in front of people, characters you sometimes don’t know, or who leave you just a few minutes to be able to make a photo.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas reality.”
This collection of portraits of the present flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at the number 20 of rue de la Mata (rue parallel to the Hercule People) which will be opened until October 16th next.
