Interview - Blood Become Safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her foundation, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Hema-Québec became one of the most safe and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained the trust of the public that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that led to such tragedy and to make recommendations for such disaster to no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was too long to file his report, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, just 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec,” Dr. Decary said.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and field work over the following years, we regained public confidence,” she said before proudly affirming that in the early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had now trusted Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary notes, however, that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the mad cow’s disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, were exhibited in Europe, tells the one that holds the fort since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was then based on that when it is not known and that a serious illness can result from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a brain degeneration leading to death inevitably is introduced exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had stayed more than a month in the UK since 1980 was therefore refused.
Now, a few years ago, it has been demonstrated out of doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied was meaningful."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV screening appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allowed to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
TANs have allowed to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood through our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, we have substantially decreased the risk that some donors are infected without knowing it and that they cannot be detected.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I think today we can feel comfortable to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health,” said Hema-Québec’s head of director.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogens will emerge in the system.
Not later that last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Reunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Decary continues before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
“Needs grow because the population grows aged.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red or platelet recharge.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network that accounts for an average of only 3% of Quebec donors eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person, 18 years old and older who meets eligibility criteria, can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they are AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is suffering, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Because today’s life is so frightened, we rarely find time spending an hour to give her blood,” Francine Décary says.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood cord bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, is full of a stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We’ve been celebrating a few weeks ago the bank of our thousandth cord blood sample and we’re planning to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Decary, which describes this cord blood sample program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed not to have access to it," because Héma-Québec has no way to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
