Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In his September 17th edition, Le Devoir published a letter by Patrick J. Garver, Vice-President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Continuing an Orwellian logic, it claims that the world’s largest airifery company has attempted a defamation prosecution of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the money to launch a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of prosecution in defamation, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely occulted by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares supporting a position contrary to his?
No matter the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defense and fight against an army of lawyers supported by the almost backgroundless pockets of the mining.
Tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a settlement on the friendly ones, which will scare the opposition in addition to fearing anyone who dares to look at the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public opinion that she should have presented her vision of facts.
Unlike what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, the debate in Canada is usually done by the exchange of ideas and not by matrack.
It was therefore enough for the mining to open its books, records and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have made the light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust the public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Maybe Mr. Garver could explain how he can simultaneously ask for a "public" debate while contemplating the opinions of the same audience?
In the world of the Vice-President, it seems that this word refers only to fat-paid lawyers and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even the detractors are entitled to speech.
What doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who supports Black Canada's authors and publishers primarily does so because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
The audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not as part of what many perceive as a pursuit (continuing the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just put a stand-up to the authors in Black Canada inciting them to cease this use).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the search for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in a block, the right to citation of credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are unpleasant to the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the writers of Black Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The academic environment, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and solve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate prosecution clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit such abuse prosecution.
