It includes, in particular, a better control by the elected of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the refund of public money engaged, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure of payment, and a right to look at salaries paid to the leaders of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Chairman of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiation table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
"All has been done in a way to protect the real economy and the ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis at Wall Street," the Democrat said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances on Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in recent hours because of fear of the effect that would cause a new failure on investors' mood.
The deadline was the opening of markets this morning.
Associated late with the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election showed themselves rather favorable to the agreement, but without expressing their dissatisfaction that we were forced to achieve it at this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has awarded himself the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the provisions aimed at allowing owners to retain their homes and that on the salary of the leaders of the government-backed companies.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of some’s irresponsibility, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked about another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, "I would like to see the details, but I hope yes."
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that this is something we’ll all have to digest and with which we’ll be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to purchase with the money of taxpayers the doubtful, risky and insolvable claims of the U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the breakdown of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of risk mortgage credits (subprimes) before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and banking and financial banking institutions.
It was a group of Republican elects who had capotered the first agreement project last week.
