In order to round the angles for everyone at the Congress, a provision was also added that if the government had to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its payment.
The new plan provides the payment of a first 250 billion range to which another 100 billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be agreed by another Congress vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain shares in the rescued companies that will be worth dividend in the event of profit and that he will be able to sell back when the torment is passed.
