The psychology of the surgery: why do we spend more money?
When auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economy at the University of New York managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the Science magazine, human beings don’t want to be distant during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay a too high price.
These researches have tried to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the groups of volunteers played lotto, while the other group participated in playing auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance process (MRI), the researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the scale of a third, the whole underneath the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, next to several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained with the leakage from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overwhelming to face a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus performed their payment.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they went out winning the game, then they would receive additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received those $15 prior to the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the focus was placed in one on victory, while in the other, on failure.
In this way proving the hypothesis of neurologs, members of the player’s team “counter failure” were ready to better bets than those made by the control group and the group “for victory”.
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed in auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to suppress the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
An estimated one hundred miles of patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment. This is because often sick people do not know they are carrying the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on pathogens, spread primarily in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperma, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowness develops on the skin and on the white eye, the stools become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, a million people each year die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to reach the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a manner. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis are figured worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor treating as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be healed, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by agencies representing sick people from all corners of the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more sustainable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article that researchers from the University of Oxford achieved an interesting experience by analyzing what level the belief in God could influence human pain tolerance.
As part of this experience for the least strange, 12 Catholic believers and so many Atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpating the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, to which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting the sparks and diffusing the electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to sustainedly watch two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the source of this experience hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, bears her calming effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, they received 20 electrochocs in four subsequent, while watching either religious theme painting or more general theme painting.
The Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like “safe,” like someone whose “care is taken” and they “calmed up, and peace invaded them.”
In view of religious thematic painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experience, believes that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image facing which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, the Anglican Bishop, welcomed the results of these researches.
“The practice of faith should change and in many cases actually changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber is shown to believers?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
