Intelligent cars mimic the bourdon’s theft
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, unless the imitation of an already existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the bees gave Nissan’s strategic starting idea to inspire them on how they need to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotized control system of type BR23C, which has equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate goal is to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own, oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell, Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the brand’s department of research and development and technology public relations, said at the exhibition.
The facet eye of the bee plays a vital role, as it is capable of seeing in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, then the mini-auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system today, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t so, the mini-auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is now considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in an eye climb.
On the opposite of the bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonal, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary movement, acceleration and slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini-auto robot.
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is larger, making their lifetime longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is essential, not the processing of data, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only handle a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvres. In this way, it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
We don't need memory of a giga-byte capacity, nor even mega-byte.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology to instantly avoid. According to Nissan’s estimates, this system will enter series-made cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding the obstacles on his way.
