In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 percent compared to the month of August 2007 - communicates the Hungary Central Statistics Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to one year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have increased only to a smaller extent: 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only a slight increase in order by 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and shoe item manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with first, the manufacturing of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then the manufacturing of shoes with 2.5 percent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6%).
A deflation resulted in oil processing sectors (1.4 percent), machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing (0.9 percent), as well as a minimum increase in wood processing sector (0.1 percent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors in the processing industry have increased between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the sectors of electrical energy, gas, steam and water supply, representing a significant weight in the national industrial exploitation, prices have increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the rise in the price of gas established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sale of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector have experienced the most significant rise (32.4 percent).
In the manufacturing sector of metallurgical products, prices were increased by 13.2 percent, while in the important field of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 percent.
Price decreases occurred in the manufacturing sectors of textile and textile products (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3 percent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price rise has evolved between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices for electrical energy, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 percent of that of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and depending on sector allocation, in August, are the investment profit initiators sectors that showed the most significant monthly price rise (0.7 percent).
In consumer goods manufacturing sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while those in energy and material manufacturing sectors for subsequent transformation did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In consumer goods production sectors, an inflation of 6.8 percent was measured, while in profit-initiating sectors a decrease of 1.4 percent.
Industrial export prices in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they dropped by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
