Mp3 reader pointed by the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening full-volume music for a prolonged period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announced, which, in a statement broadcast in Brussels, cites the Scientific Committee's opinion on the EU's unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri), published today.
“In this scientific report we read, it shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least five years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than an hour a day and week, are at risk of a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” said Meglena Kuneva.
“According to the scientific data,” the Ue manager continues, “this is a clear risk and we need to respond quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumers awareness and make this domain information public.
In addition, we need to review the existing control systems in view of scientific opinion, so that they are completely effective and can follow new technologies.”
Brussels requested the Independent Scientific Committee to consider the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"The scientists, concluded by the executive Ue, confirm that there are good reasons to worry about, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other stakeholders, which measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but an increased concern about hearing damage that could derive from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to well limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, listening to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed currently existing limits for the maximum noise level consented on the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for prolonged periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to approximately 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
